## 3. Ghost

*Immutable continuity (Track C — Memory Spine)*

The **Ghost** is ORIC's memory spine.

It is **append-only** and **non-executive**.

It preserves continuity without becoming a controller — because:

- memory that can be rewritten becomes propaganda
- memory that can command becomes tyranny

So the Ghost is built around a single invariant:

> **Observer may constrain. Human may override. Ghost never executes.**

**The Ghost Contract (invariants)**

A sovereign Ghost MUST be:

```
MUST BE (Sovereign Memory)          MUST NOT BE (Surveillance)
──────────────────────────          ──────────────────────────
Append-only (no rewrite)            Editable history
Consent-bound                       External ownership
Auditable / traceable               Opaque scoring
Forkable interpretations            Single enforced narrative
Non-executive (cannot trade)        Action-authority
Truth anchored in exchange          Truth anchored in story
```

**Forking as growth without propaganda**

Forking allows the system to evolve interpretation without rewriting history:

- Parent entry remains immutable
- Forks add perspective without altering the record
- Synthesis learns without coercion

The Ghost does not say "do this again."

It whispers: "This is familiar. Notice how you treated ambiguity last time."

> Memory without sovereignty is surveillance.
> Sovereignty without memory is amnesia.

